Project - Twitter US Airline Sentiment¶

Data Description:¶

A sentiment analysis job about the problems of each major U.S. airline. Twitter data was scraped from February of 2015 and contributors were asked to first classify positive, negative, and neutral tweets, followed by categorizing negative reasons (such as "late flight" or "rude service").

Dataset:¶

The dataset has the following columns:

  • tweet_id
  • airline_sentiment
  • airline_sentiment_confidence
  • negativereason
  • negativereason_confidence
  • airline
  • airline_sentiment_gold
  • name
  • negativereason_gold
  • retweet_count
  • text
  • tweet_coord
  • tweet_created
  • tweet_location
  • user_timezone

#Function to create barplots that indicate percentage for each category
def perc_on_bar(feature):
    #Creating a countplot for the feature
    sns.set(rc={'figure.figsize':(20,10)})
    ax=sns.countplot(x=feature, data=data,hue = data['airline_sentiment'])
    
    total = len(feature) # length of the column
    for p in ax.patches:
        percentage = '{:.1f}%'.format(100 * p.get_height()/total) # percentage of each class of the category
        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2 - 0.25 # width of the plot
        y = p.get_y() + p.get_height()           # hieght of the plot
        ax.annotate(percentage, (x, y), size = 10) # annotate the percantage 
        
    plt.show() # show the plot

plot_data = data.copy()

import wordcloud
def show_wordcloud(df, title):
    text = ' '.join(df['text'].astype(str).tolist())                 # Converting Summary column into list
    stopwords = set(wordcloud.STOPWORDS)                                  # instantiate the stopwords from wordcloud
    
    fig_wordcloud = wordcloud.WordCloud(stopwords=stopwords,background_color='white',          # Setting the different parameter of stopwords
                    colormap='viridis', width=800, height=600).generate(text)
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(14,11), frameon=True)                             
    plt.imshow(fig_wordcloud)  
    plt.axis('off')
    plt.title(title, fontsize=30)
    plt.show()

# a. HTML tag removal
def strip_html(text):
  soup = BeautifulSoup(text, 'html.parser')
  return soup.get_text()

data1['text'] = data1['text'].apply(lambda x: strip_html(x))

# c. Remove numbers 
def remove_numbers(words):
  new_words = []
  for word in words:
    new_word = re.sub(r'\d', '', word)
    if new_word != '':
      new_words.append(new_word)
  return new_words

# d. Remove of Special Characters and Punctuations.
def remove_special_characters_punctuation(words):
  new_words =[]
  for word in words:
    new_word = re.sub(r'[^\w\s]', '', word)
    new_word = re.sub(r'[^a-zA-Z0-9]', '', new_word)
    if new_word != '':
      new_words.append(new_word)
  return new_words

# e. Removal of stopwords
stopwords = stopwords.words('english')
stopwords
def remove_stopwords(words):
  """ Remove stop words from list of tokenized words"""
  new_words = []
  for word in words:
    if word not in stopwords:
      new_words.append(word)
  return new_words

# f. convert lower case
def convert_lower_case(words):
  new_words = []
  for word in words:
    new_word = word.lower()
    new_words.append(new_word)
  return new_words

# g. Lemmatize or stemming.
lemmatizer = WordNetLemmatizer()
def lemmatize_list(words):
    new_words = []
    for word in words:
      new_words.append(lemmatizer.lemmatize(word, pos='v'))
    return new_words

def normalize(words):
  words = remove_numbers(words)
  words = remove_special_characters_punctuation(words)
  words = remove_stopwords(words)
  words = convert_lower_case(words)
  words = lemmatize_list(words)
  return ' '.join(words)
# h. i.
data1['text'] = data1.apply(lambda row: normalize(row['text']), axis=1)
data1.head()

Optimizing the parameters: Number of trees in the random foret model (n_estimators)¶

In [29]:
# Finding optimal number of base learners using K-ford CV

base_ln = [x for x in range(1,30)]

# K-Fold Cross - Validation. 
cv_score = []
for b in base_ln:
  clf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators= b)
  scores = cross_val_score(clf, X_train, y_train, cv= 5, scoring='accuracy')
  cv_score.append(scores.mean())
In [30]:
# plotting the error as k increase

error = [1 - x for x in cv_score]
optimal_learners = base_ln[error.index(min(error))]

plt.plot(base_ln, error)
xy = (optimal_learners, min(error))
plt.annotate('(%s, %s' % xy, xy = xy, textcoords ='data')
plt.xlabel("Number of base learners")
plt.ylabel("Misclassification Error")
plt.show()
  • Learner at 21,24, 25 provide less error. Let's go with 25 since it went straight line after that.

Summary:¶

  • We used a dataset which has reviews in text format and their airline_sentiment of neutral, positive, and negative.
  • The goal was to build a model for text-classification.
  • We pre-processed the data using various techniques and libraries.
  • We created Word Cloud plots of top 40 features
  • The pre-processed data is converted to numbers (Vectorized [CountVectorizer, TF-IDF]), so that we can feed the data into the model.
  • We trained the model and optimized the paramter(n_estimators), which lead to an increase the overall accuaracy.
  • We predicted the results for the test data.
  • The model can be improve by increasing max_features paramters in the vectorizer, using grid search cv to do hyperparmeter turning, and other pre-processing techniques to increase the overall accuracy even further.
